{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503697","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503697"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:06:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:06:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2070"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2070","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2070"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.16,0.11,0.66,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2070"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65950"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2070","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2070"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2070"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51399"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"188"},{"type":"tags","id":"2840"},{"type":"tags","id":"2845"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"83"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9203"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9222"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16137"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22037"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42449"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65950","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65950"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset of muscle stiffness, neck twisting, and upward deviation of the eyes. He was started on oral haloperidol 5 mg two days ago for aggressive behaviour associated with schizophrenia. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He smokes 10 cigarettes per day and drinks alcohol occasionally. There is a family history of schizophrenia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed. His pulse rate is 86/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. His neck is twisted to one side, and his eyes are deviated upwards. The rest of the neurological examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Naloxone 0.4 mg intravenously","Increase haloperidol dose to 10 mg orally","Benztropine 2 mg orally","Benztropine 2 mg intramuscularly","Supportive care and reassurance"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is presenting with acute dystonia, a movement disorder characterized by involuntary muscle contractions leading to abnormal postures or movements. In this case, it is likely caused by the recent initiation of haloperidol, an antipsychotic medication known for its strong dopamine D2 receptor blockade.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBenztropine 2 mg intramuscularly\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step in management. Acute dystonia is best treated with parenteral anticholinergic medication, with intramuscular or intravenous benztropine being the first-line choice. This rapidly counteracts the dopamine blockade causing the dystonia and provides quick relief of symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENaloxone 0.4 mg intravenously\u003C/strong\u003E is used to reverse opioid overdose. There is no indication of opioid use in this patient, and his symptoms are not consistent with opioid toxicity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing haloperidol dose to 10 mg orally\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate and potentially harmful. Increasing the antipsychotic dose would likely worsen the dystonic reaction by further increasing dopamine blockade.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBenztropine 2 mg orally\u003C/strong\u003E, while the correct medication, is not the best route of administration for acute dystonia. Oral medications have a slower onset of action compared to parenteral routes, which is crucial in this acute situation. Typically oral benztropine is only administered upon resolution of acute dystonia after initial signs have been relieved in which case 1-2 mg is administered up to twice daily as required, for a two week duration with down titration towards the end, as per the Therapeutic Guidelines.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESupportive care and reassurance\u003C/strong\u003E, while important aspects of patient care, are insufficient for managing acute dystonia. Active pharmacological intervention is necessary to relieve the patient\u0027s distressing symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAcute dystonia typically occurs within the first few days of starting or increasing the dose of an antipsychotic medication, particularly those with high potency or strong D2 receptor blockade like haloperidol. It\u0027s important to recognize this adverse effect promptly and treat it appropriately to prevent patient distress and potential non-adherence to necessary antipsychotic treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Intramuscular or intravenous benztropine is the first-line treatment for acute dystonia caused by antipsychotic medications.","Acute dystonia typically occurs within days of starting or increasing the dose of an antipsychotic medication, especially those with strong D2 receptor blockade.","Acute dystonia presents with involuntary muscle contractions, often affecting the neck, eyes, and trunk."],"references":["Therapeutic guidelines [online]. 2023; Accessed: 2023 Jun 8. Available at: https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/","Acute dystonia treatment. In: UpToDate [online]. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/treatment-of-dystonia-in-children-and-adults/print","Barow E, Schneider SA, Bhatia KP, Ganos C. Oculogyric crises: Etiology, pathophysiology and therapeutic approaches. Parkinsonism Relat Disord. 2017;36:3-9. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27964831/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51399"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2070"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51399","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51399"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-28T09:22:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-28T09:22:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2070"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65950"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position